# README
This README is for VSCODE-extension "reftext" language support/coloring. (github.com/dolphin00012/reftext).
This regex (regular expression) extension for vscode provides support for 'reftext' language coloring some
parts of text files for may 'better' decipherering "notes" against already published "{literature refferences
titles}" whilst viewing (!), letting the pure 'uft8 po what else text/signs' stored file completly untouched.

# INSTALLATION
1. Download and install Visual Studio Code (https://vscode.dev - but vsix is not on marketplace yet or 
   https://code.visualstudio.com/download - on a lot hardware devices installable, for android otherewise
   yet 'only' an alternative installable i dont know if that app can install vsix's from local locations).
2. Install the related .vsix file to vscode (github.com/dolphi8n00012/reftext/reftext-*version*.vsix).
3. ADD some code to your own (eg. to C:\Users\*username*\AppData\Roaming\Code\User\settings.json) file:
   "editor.tokenColorCustomizations": {
   "textMateRules": [
   {"scope": "dotword.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#00ff00" }},
   {"scope": "asteriskword.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#00ff00" }},
   {"scope": "IN.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#ffee03" }},
   {"scope": "headline.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#fc05b2" }},
   {"scope": "comment.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#17c017" }},
   {"scope": "year.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#00AEFF" }},
   {"scope": "comma.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#ffee03" }},
   {"scope": "else.in.reftext", "settings": { "foreground": "#cfcfcf" }}]},

# FEATURES
1. if a line begins with at least one "#" = a (foldable) title line + pink colored text in that line.
2. if aline beings with "word." = that 1st word is colored green.
3. if a phrase is surrounded by "{}" = the inner text is colored white (instead of grey) and any 4digits is
   automatically shown in blue color (like a 4digits one my would use for scientific literature pdf file naming.
4. any text or 'signs' outside {} brackets is colored automatically grey.
5. olored green (at least if not a "#" at the beginning line, and only if outside {}'s).

# USAGE
1. Open a "file" even a 'README' without extension. in vscode, then change "language" (lower right of vscode
   app window to 'reftext'. -> than see colorization in action.
2. Change ADDED "code lines" to ones own "settings.json":




